 and working-class parents in Taiwan, and middle-class and working-class Chinese immigrants in the Boston area. Despite sharing a similar ethnic cultural background, these parents develop class-specific, context-sensitive strategies for arranging their children's education, care, and discipline, and for coping with uncertainties provoked by their changing surroundings. Lan's cross-Pacific comparison demonstrates that class inequality permeates the fabric of family life, even as it takes shape in different ways across national contexts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aChild rearingzTaiwan. 0aChild rearingzUnited States. 0aChinese AmericansxFamily relationships. 0aFamilieszTaiwan. 0aImmigrant familieszUnited States. 0aSocial classeszTaiwan. 0aSocial classeszUnited States. 0aTaiwanese AmericansxFamily relationships. 4aChinese immigrants. 4aChinese parenting. 4aTaiwan. 4acultural negotiation. 4aglobalization. 4aparenting and social class. 4atransnational mobility. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Complete eBook-Package 2018z978311070368940uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150360591640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503605916423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781503605916.jpg  a978-3-11-070368-9  SUP Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles